		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Things that pisses me off with emulators</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">1) Annoyances to define joypad buttons.</div><br />Loopynes made you define all joystick buttons whenever you wanted to redefine controls, but the process was so streamlined that it was painless.  Only 8 keypresses.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">2) No debugging features<br /></div><br />Totally agree with you here, I liked how Snemul would let you see graphics and palettes, even when its emulation wasn't up to the standards of Zsnes or Snes9x.  For Sega Master System/Gamegear, I like to use Emukon, because it lets you see the graphics.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">3) New version has less features than old version / is not compatible with old save states<br /></div><br />This is really hard to pull off.  Sometimes you rewrite such a big chunk of the emulator, and you need to quickly implement savestates for the new features, so you just dump the variables and throw it in a file.  But then your new version doesn't have things organized the same way, so the new version's savestates become incompatible.  So if you need backwards compatibility, you end up with 50 different versions of the loadstate function.  That can get yucky really quick.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">4) Saves in their own folder instead of ROM folder<br /></div><br />If you put your Roms on a CD, or on a read-only network share, you will need a separate folder.  I guess this is part of the old-style vs new-style divide here, old style is that you threw files on the C:\ drive, and made directories, and threw everything together.  New style is to use the Document and Settings tree, possibly even *gasp* the Application Data folder.  And nobody agrees whether to save things in My Documents, or Application Data, or wherever.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">5) Not regularly overwriting the SAVE file.<br /></div><br />I remember when ZSNES added to the &quot;SRAM Check and Save&quot; feature, and that was a big deal.<br />But you can't blindly save the SRAM every time there's a write there, some games (Super Mario land 2) even use the save ram as the system stack.  I guess periodic checking and saving is the way to go here.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">6) Don't play the ROM automatically / Can't drag and drop / Can't associate with the file extension<br /></div><br />Yeah, Nintendulator dropped the ball here.  Also NO$GBA makes you start the game manually.  But there are situations where you want to get your debugger ready before any code executes.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


