	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">1) Annoyances to define joypad buttons.</div>Amen. This is always a sore point when using a new emulator. You'd have loved QuickNES for Mac. Configure keys, it shows a box with rectangles at each button locations that show the current key for the button. You can either click on a button you want to set, then press that button. Or, Up is already selected, and if you hit your button for up, it moves on to Down, then Left, Right, etc. so you basically just hit 8 keys to redefine, then you're done.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">5) Not regularly overwriting the SAVE file.</div>At least on Mac OS, one can write their saving using a &quot;safe save&quot;, which writes the new data to a new temporary file, then swaps that temporary file's data with the old file's data and updates the modification date. This is an atomic operation, where any failure along the way either leaves the old intact file, or the new one, never a corrupt file.<br /><br />7) No Recently Played menu.<br /><br />The emulator should keep track of the most recent few games I've played, so that if I'm playing them regularly, I can just open the emulator and select them from the menu. And it should reload the last save file for that game as well.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
