	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>mic_</b> [ Wed Feb 06, 2013 3:55 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Things that pisses me off with emulators</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">it's horrible that more than half of the emus around have ZERO debugging features. No VRAM viewer, no Palette viewer, no debugger, etc.. This is so annoying. Especially considering they probably HAD to implement them for the development of the emulator</div><br /><br />I agree that a lack of debugging features in an emulator is annoying. At the same time, I can see why this is the case. Most people develop NES emulators as a hobby, not as a job, so they'll work on whatever part of the emulator that they find the most interesting. Debugging features and the sometimes-complex GUI programming that can come with it probably won't place very high on any &quot;Fun things to do in emulation&quot; list. Sure, a palette viewer is usually trivial to do, but something like a decent disassembler with stepping, breakpoints and watches is not.<br />I'd also guess that most emulators are geared towards gaming rather than homebrew development, which probably contributes to emulator authors' lack of interest in adding debugging features (combined with the fact that there's so much information available about systems like the NES that the emulator authors themselves typically can get along just fine by just adding some prints here and there in many cases).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


