		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">whatever part of the emulator that they find the most interesting. Debugging features and the sometimes-complex GUI programming that can come with it probably won't place very high on any &quot;Fun things to do in emulation&quot; list.</div><br />I completely disagree with you ! Even if you don't develop much for a system its incredibly fun, and interesting, to see how your favourite (or less favourite) games works internally.<br /><br />I spend hours watching the nametables and pattern tables of NES games being updated during game-play, and I actually find this just as fun as playing.<br /><br />Also I don't ask them to add debugging features (even if this would be the best), just not to remove them, as it's likely impossible to develop an emulator without any debugging features, how can you trace your emulation bugs then ?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Because the change results in something visible to the emulated program.</div><br />And that's what makes it interesting. Also they didn't remove the possibility to individually enable/disable BG layers, even though it results in something visible to the emulated program.<br /><br />I find it quite interesting to see &quot;hey they did this effect by changing the scroll with HDMA midframe ? Oh and it would look like this without the effect ?&quot;.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">How so, if the model of the emulated machine doesn't match the other emulators' models, or if the other emulators' models aren't published (such as closed-source emulators)?</div><br />Sure, but it's still a nice thing to do and has been done before. Old versions of SNES9x could load ZST savestates, and I'm sure there was an NES emulator that was compatible with NESTicle save states.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
